{"title_page": "Arghun Aqa", "text_new": "{{hatnote|For the leader of the Ilkhanate in the late 13th century, grandson of Hulagu, see [[Arghun]].}}{{Infobox officeholder\n| name                = Arghun Aqa\n| office              = [[Darughachi]] of [[Persia]], [[Georgia]] and [[Anatolia]]\n| termstart           = 1243\n| termend             = 1275\n| predecessor         = [[Korguz]]\n| successor           = [[Buqa]]\n| birth_date          = {{circa|1210}}\n| death_date          = {{death date and age|1275|6|17|1210|mf=yes}}\n| office1             = Deputy Governor of [[Greater Khorasan|Khorasan]]\n| termstart1          = 1265\n| termend1            = 1275\n| governor1           = Prince Tubshin\n| death_place         = [[Greater Khorasan|Khorasan]]\n}}\n'''Arghun Agha''', also '''Arghun Aqa''' or '''Arghun the Elder''' ({{Lang-fa|\u0627\u0631\u063a\u0648\u0646 \u0622\u0642\u0627}}; {{Lang-mn|\u1820\u1837\u182d\u1824\u1828}}; {{Floruit|1220}} - 1275) was a [[Mongol Empire|Mongol]] noble of the [[Oirats|Oirat]] clan in the 13th century. He was a governor in the Mongol-controlled area of [[Persia]] from 1243 to 1255, before the [[Ilkhanate]] was created by [[Hulagu]].<ref>Grousset, p. 376</ref>  Arghun Agha was in control of the four districts of eastern and central Persia, as decreed by the great khan [[M\u00f6ngke Khan]].\n\n== Early life ==\nAccording to [[Rashid-al-Din Hamadani|Rashid al-Din]], when he was young, his father sold his son Arghun to Qadan of the [[Jalayir]], tutor of [[\u00d6gedei Khan|\u00d6gedei]]<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Landa|first=Ishayahu|date=2018|title=New Light on Early Mongol Islamisation: The Case of Arghun Aqa's Family|url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/journal-of-the-royal-asiatic-society/article/new-light-on-early-mongol-islamisation-the-case-of-arghun-aqas-family1/EBC828779461678CFCFDCE46ED89BB86|journal=Journal of the Royal Asiatic Society|language=en|volume=28|issue=1|pages=77\u2013100|doi=10.1017/S1356186317000438|issn=1356-1863|via=}}</ref> who passed him to his son Il\u00fcge,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/argun-aqa-a-mongol-administrator-in-iran-d-1275|title=AR\u1e20\u016aN \u0100Q\u0100 \u2013 Encyclopaedia Iranica|website=www.iranicaonline.org|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> while according to [[Ata-Malik Juvayni|Juvayni]] his father was a [[mingghan]] commander.<ref>[[Ata-Malik Juvayni|Ata-Malik Juvaini]], ''[[Tarikh-i Jahangushay|Genghis Khan: The History of  the World-Conqueror]]'' trans. J. A. Boyle (Manchester, 1997), p. 505. </ref> During his years with the [[House of Ogedei|Ogedeyid]] family, he gained reputation among the members of the ruling blood because he was well educated and versed in [[Old Uyghur language]]. Arghun started his career as ''bitikchi'' (secretary) in during the reign of \u00d6gedei. Later on, the latter's consort, [[Toregene Khatun]], appointed him as then governor of Transoxiana - [[Korguz]]'s ''[[basqaq]]'' and ultimately overall civil governor after [[Korguz]]'s execution in {{Circa|1242}}.\n\n== Career ==\nHe was appointed to oversee vast lands from [[Amu Darya|Oxus]] to [[Anatolia]] with Sharaf al-Din Khwarazmi as his secretary, whom he had a distaste in.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Lane|first=George|date=1999|title=Arghun Aqa: Mongol bureaucrat|url=http://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/00210869908701965|journal=Iranian Studies|language=en|volume=32|issue=4|pages=459\u2013482|doi=10.1080/00210869908701965|issn=0021-0862|via=}}</ref> His position was reaffirmed by [[G\u00fcy\u00fck Khan]] in 1246. [[Ascelin of Lombardia]] might have met him while he was at the court of [[Baiju]] in {{Circa|1247}}. He visited [[Karakorum]] twice after his appointment in 1248 and 1251. On his third voyage, he was upheld by [[Hulagu Khan|Hulagu]] in Transoxiana and was released after a while. His employees included the famous [[Juvayni family]], Fakr al-Din Bihishti (d. 1256), Husam al-Din Bihishti, Najm al-Din Ali, Turumtai, Naimadai and etc. He made a census in Persia in accordance with the decree of [[M\u00f6ngke Khan|M\u00f6ngke]] in 1254 along with Najm al-Din Ali.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nIn 1259-61 he directed punitive operations against rebels in [[Kingdom of Georgia|Georgia]], and then was sent to [[Greater Khorasan|Khorasan]] to fight the [[Golden Horde]]. He is described as faithful servant of the Qaghan in [[Persia]]n sources while the [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]]n and [[Armenia]]n sources say he was cruel and violent overseer. However, one Georgian chronicle mentions he was a friend of equity, trustful in his language, a deep thinker, and profound in counsel. It also says Arghun conducted the empire-wide census in [[Russia]], [[Arctic]], [[Alania]], [[Pontic steppe]], Georgia, Armenia, and [[Anatolia]].<ref>H.H.Howrth-HOM, Mongols in Persia, vol.III. p.68</ref> Arghun had many political enemies at the headquarters, so he had to visit the [[ordo (palace)|''ordo'']] of the Qaghan in [[Mongolia]] often to prove his loyalty. Although, M\u00f6ngke appointed him to his former position after his accession in 1252, the Emperor summoned Arghun to answer a charge of treason. The [[Armenian people|Armenian]] noble, [[Orbelian Dynasty|Sempad Orpelian]], justified Arghun completely and charged his enemy, a [[Khorazm]]i lieutenant, with being the real offender.<ref>H.H.Howorth, HOM, Mongols in Persia, vol.III. p.65</ref> Arghun was released and they returned together.\n\n=== Under Hulagu ===\nHe mainted his administrative tasks under Hulagu and even punished underpaying vassals who owed them taxes, including [[Gvantsa Kakhaberidze]], [[Hasan Jalal|Hasan Jalal of Khachen]], [[Zakare III Zakarian]], [[Akhsitan II]] and others in 1261. He accompained [[Abaqa Khan|Prince Abaqa]] in support of [[Alghu]] against his struggle with [[Golden Horde]].\n\n=== Under Abaqa ===\n[[File:\u0631\u0627\u062f\u06a9\u0627\u0646.jpg|thumb|415x415px|''Mil-i Radkan'' is believed to be tomb of Arghun Aqa]]\nArghun continued to serve Ilkhanate after death of Hulagu in 1265. His new post was in [[Khorasan Province|Khorasan]], as deputy of Prince Tubshin. New Chagatai khan [[Ghiyas-ud-din Baraq|Baraq]] threatened to invade Ilkhanate until they leave [[Afghanistan]] to them in 1270. Arghun Aqa fought in left flank under [[Yoshmut|Prince Yoshmut]] in Battle of Herat on 22 July 1270 which resulted in a decisive victory. He served in Khorasan till his death on 17 June 1275.\n\n== Legacy ==\nHe appears to have funded [[Pir Huseyn Khanqah]] in [[Qubal\u0131balao\u011flan]], modern [[Azerbaijan]]. He is thought to be buried in [[Radkan, Razavi Khorasan|Radkan]], Khorasan.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Family ==\nShe had many wives, including a daughter of [[Yes\u00fc M\u00f6ngke]], to whom he married in 1249. Another wife of his was S\u00fcrmish, who gave birth to Nawruz.<ref name=\":0\" /> He had at least 14 sons and 4 daughters<ref name=\":0\" />:\n\n* A son (died 1270 in [[Herat]])\n* Girai Malik\n* Tatarji\n* [[Nawr\u016bz (Mongol emir)|Nawruz]] (d. 13 August 1297)\n* Lagzi G\u00fcregen (d. 2 April 1297) \u2014 married to Baba Khatun (daughter of [[Hulagu Khan|Hulagu]])\n** Terjughan Khatun \u2014 married to [[\u00d6ljait\u00fc]]\n* Hajji\n* Tarkhan Hajji\n** A daughter \u2014 married Fakhr al-Din ibn Rukn al-Din of [[Kart dynasty|Kartids]] (1295\u20131308)\n* Yol Qutlugh \n* Bulquq\n* Oiratai\n* Ertai Ghazan (d. 1297)\n* Narin Hajji (d. 1297, [[Hamadan]])\n* Arghun Hajji\n* Mengli Buqa\n* Barghun Hajji\n* Emine Khatun (died {{Circa|1300}} and buried in [[Salmas]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenelsoncollection.co.uk/artworks/categories/3/9515/|title=Antoin Sevruguin, The tomb of Emir Arghun Agha's daughter, Salmas, Late 19th Century|website=The Nelson Collection of Qajar Photography|language=en|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref>) \u2014 possibly married to Taj al-Din 'Ali Shah, vizier.\n* Begi Khatun or Ilkuye Begi \u2014 married to [[Muzaffar al-Din Hajjaj]] in 1263/4<ref name=\":0\" />\n* A daughter \u2014 married to Kingsh\u00fc, son of [[Jumghur]]<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Landa|first=Ishayahu|date=2018|title=Oirats in the Ilkhanate and the Mamluk Sultanate in the Thirteenth to the Early Fifteenth Centuries: Two Cases of Assimilation into the Muslim Environment (MSR XIX, 2016)|url=https://knowledge.uchicago.edu/record/1187|doi=10.6082/M1B27SG2}}</ref>\n* Menglitegin \u2014 married to Amir Tasu of [[Eljigin]] clan of [[Khongirad]]\n** Bulughan Khatun Khorasani \u2014 married to [[Ghazan]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n* Amitai-Preiss, ''Mongols and Mamluks: the Mamluk-\u012alkh\u0101nid War, 1260-1281''\n* Rene Grousset, ''The Empire of the Steppes''\n{{High-ranking ministers and commanders of the Mongol Empire}}\n\n\n[[Category:1278 deaths]]\n[[Category:People of the Ilkhanate]]\n[[Category:Heads of state of Iran]]\n[[Category:Mongol Empire people]]\n[[Category:Oirats]]\n[[Category:Year of birth unknown]]\n\n\n{{mongolia-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{hatnote|For the leader of the Ilkhanate in the late 13th century, grandson of Hulagu, see [[Arghun]].}}\n\n{{Infobox noble|name=Arghun Aqa|death_date={{Death date|1275|6|17}}|title=Mongol Governor of [[Persia]]|successor=[[Hulagu]]|predecessor=[[Korguz]]|reign=1243 - 1255|reign-type=In office|house-type=|birth_date=c. 1210}}\n\n'''Arghun Agha''', also '''Arghun Aqa''' or '''Arghun the Elder''' ({{Lang-fa|\u0627\u0631\u063a\u0648\u0646 \u0622\u0642\u0627}}; {{Lang-mn|\u1820\u1837\u182d\u1824\u1828}}; {{Floruit|1220}} - 1278) was a [[Mongol Empire|Mongol]] noble of the [[Oirats|Oirat]] clan in the 13th century. He was a governor in the Mongol-controlled area of [[Persia]] from 1243 to 1255, before the [[Ilkhanate]] was created by [[Hulagu]].<ref>Grousset, p. 376</ref>  Arghun Agha was in control of the four districts of eastern and central Persia, as decreed by the great khan [[M\u00f6ngke Khan]].\n\n== Early life ==\nAccording to [[Rashid-al-Din Hamadani|Rashid al-Din]], when he was young, his father sold his son Arghun to Qadan of the [[Jalayir]], tutor of [[\u00d6gedei Khan|\u00d6gedei]]<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Landa|first=Ishayahu|date=2018|title=New Light on Early Mongol Islamisation: The Case of Arghun Aqa's Family|url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/journal-of-the-royal-asiatic-society/article/new-light-on-early-mongol-islamisation-the-case-of-arghun-aqas-family1/EBC828779461678CFCFDCE46ED89BB86|journal=Journal of the Royal Asiatic Society|language=en|volume=28|issue=1|pages=77\u2013100|doi=10.1017/S1356186317000438|issn=1356-1863|via=}}</ref> who passed him to his son Il\u00fcge,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/argun-aqa-a-mongol-administrator-in-iran-d-1275|title=AR\u1e20\u016aN \u0100Q\u0100 \u2013 Encyclopaedia Iranica|website=www.iranicaonline.org|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> while according to [[Ata-Malik Juvayni|Juvayni]] his father was a [[mingghan]] commander.<ref>[[Ata-Malik Juvayni|Ata-Malik Juvaini]], ''[[Tarikh-i Jahangushay|Genghis Khan: The History of  the World-Conqueror]]'' trans. J. A. Boyle (Manchester, 1997), p. 505. </ref> During his years with the [[House of Ogedei|Ogedeyid]] family, he gained reputation among the members of the ruling blood because he was well educated and versed in [[Old Uyghur language]]. Arghun started his career as ''bitikchi'' (secretary) in during the reign of \u00d6gedei. Later on, the latter's consort, [[Toregene Khatun]], appointed him as then governor of Transoxiana - [[Korguz]]'s ''[[basqaq]]'' and ultimately overall civil governor after [[Korguz]]'s execution in {{Circa|1242}}.\n\n== Career ==\nHe was appointed to oversee vast lands from [[Amu Darya|Oxus]] to [[Anatolia]] with Sharaf al-Din Khwarazmi as his secretary, whom he had a distaste in.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Lane|first=George|date=1999|title=Arghun Aqa: Mongol bureaucrat|url=http://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/00210869908701965|journal=Iranian Studies|languag